  "annotations": {
    "summary": "System entropy is critically low, which can impact cryptographic operations.",
    "description": "üßê **Why This Happens**\n- Lack of sufficient hardware-generated randomness.\n- Virtual machines without hardware RNG support.\n- High demand for random numbers from cryptographic operations (SSL/TLS).\n\nüîç **Impact**\n- SSL/TLS handshake delays.\n- Possible failure in cryptographic key generation.\n- Sluggish application performance relying on /dev/random.\n\n‚úÖ **Immediate Actions for Ops**\n1. **Check current entropy level:**\n   ```\n   cat /proc/sys/kernel/random/entropy_avail\n   ```\n2. If low (<1000):\n   - Install and start `haveged` or `rngd`:\n     ```\n     sudo apt-get install haveged\n     sudo systemctl start haveged\n     ```\n   - Or for RHEL/CentOS:\n     ```\n     sudo yum install rng-tools\n     sudo systemctl start rngd\n     ```\n3. Check if hardware RNG is available (via `rngd -r /dev/hwrng`).\n4. For VMs, enable `virtio-rng` device.\n5. Monitor entropy usage by cryptographic services.\n\n‚ö† **Note:** This alert triggers if `entropy_avail` remains below **1000** for 5 minutes."
  },
